'''Herbert Smith''' was a British businessman in Hong Kong. He was a partner of the [[Jardine, Matheson & Co.]] and member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].

Smith joined Jardine, Matheson & Co., the then biggest trading firm in the Far East, and became the partner by being authorised to sign in 1876, replacing Edward Whitehall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1876/692359.pdf|date=20 May 1876|page=247|title=Notice |work=The Hongkong Government Gazette}}</ref> Smith also became partner of the  [[Butterfield & Swire]] in 1892.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1892/649930.pdf|date=7 May 1892|page=397|title=Notice|work=The Hongkong Government Gazette}}</ref> In 1897, he was appointed member of the committee for the Diamond Jubilee of [[Queen Victoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1897/635470.pdf|date=17 March 1897|title=Government Notification No. - 97 |work=The Hongkong Government Gazette Extraordinary}}</ref> He was provisionally appointed to the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] during the absence of [[T. H. Whitehead]] in 1900.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunzi.lib.hku.hk/hkgro/view/g1900/507177.pdf|date=5 March 1900|title=Government Notification - No. 211|work=The Hongkong Government Gazette|page=638}}</ref>

